    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA216-kiḷavi">itu talaimakaṭkup pāṅkiyiṉār kēṭpat talaimakaṉ talainiṉ ṟoḻukappaṭāniṉṟa parattai pāṇarkkāyiṉum viṟaliyarkkāyiṉuñ colluvāḷāy neruṅkic colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is the other woman, in front of whom HE was standing, said directed to, as one speaking to be it the bards, be it the dancing girl, so that those close to HER would hear.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA216">
<l>            tuṉitīr kūṭṭamoṭu tuṉṉā rāyiṉu</l>
<l>            miṉitō kāṇunark kāṇpuḻi vāḻtal</l>
<l>            kaṇṇuṟu viḻumaṅ kaipō lutavi</l>
<l>            nammuṟu tuyaraṅ kaḷaiyā rāyiṉu</l>
<l>            miṉṉā taṉṟē yavari lūrē </l>
<l>            yerimaruḷ vēṅkaik kaṭavuḷ kākkuṅ</l>
<l>            kurukār kaḻaṉiyi ṉitaṇat tāṅka</l>
<l>            ṇēti lāḷaṉ kavalai kavaṟṟa</l>
<l>            vorumulai yaṟutta tirumā vuṇṇik</l>
<l>            kēṭṭō raṉaiyā rāyiṉum </l>
<l>            vēṭṭō rallatu piṟariṉ ṉārē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">Even if he doesn’t approach [us] with union to end the disgust,</l>
<l>is it pleasing to live while seeing the one that sees(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kāṇunar</term> is explained here by T.V.G. as someone who is nice to look at, and indeed this would make sense out of this sentence, and it would even refer to a topos, because without parallels for such a use of the present participle this seems a little arbitrary.</note>?</l>
<l rend="indent">Even if he doesn’t remove the misery we have,</l>
<l rend="indent2">helping as a hand would [help]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kai pōl utavi</term>: here for once the "Indo-European-minded" simile structure - the absolutive not integrated into the simile.</note> the distress of the eye,</l>
<l>not unpleasant is the village without him.</l>
<l rend="indent">Even if he is one that has heard</l>
<l rend="indent2">of Tirumāvuṇṇi who tore off one of [her] breasts,<note place="foot">Here doubtless a reference related to the <term xml:lang="ta">Cilappatikāram</term> plot connected with <term xml:lang="ta">Kaṇṇaki</term>. But is it the <term xml:lang="ta">Cilappatikāram</term>? Is breast-tearing simply a topos? The name given here, that is, <term xml:lang="ta">Tirumāvuṇṇi</term>, does not seem to be attested otherwise.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">when a stranger caused [her] great distress,</l>
<l rend="indent3">there on the platform in the fields where the herons become full,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the god guards the flame-like Vēṅkai tree,</l>
<l>besides wanting others(?)<note place="foot">T.V.G. gives a particularly baroque and complicated interpretation of these last two lines that is simply beyond me. The translation given above makes sense with respect to the topic: HE now shows his favours to other women. But syntactically it is awkward: if the <term xml:lang="ta">piṟar</term> is supposed to be the direct object of <term xml:lang="ta">vēṭṭōr</term>, it ought to be put at the beginning of the line.</note>, he is not kind.</l>
      </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
